{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488733"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/521"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.11,0.74,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43803"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"8842"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe pain in his right eye after being struck with a cricket ball. It is suspected he might have a blow-out fracture of the orbit. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most suggestive of this diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subconjunctival haemorrhage","Trismus","Hyphaema","Diplopia on upward or downward gaze","Prolapse of the iris"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBlow-out orbital fractures are most closely associated with entrapment or injury of the extraocular muscles as they are the structures closest to the boney orbit surrounding the globe that is located in the center. The most commonly affected walls are the medial wall and the inferior wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFracture of the inferior orbital wall may damage the inferior oblique (IO) muscle and/or inferior rectus (IR) muscles. This may cause limitation on elevation or depression of the eye as the entrapment causes paretic and restrictive diplopia (ie. \u003Cstrong\u003Ediplopia on upward or downward gaze).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubconjunctival hemorrhage, hyphema, \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E prolapse of the iris \u003C/strong\u003Eare all signs of globe injury (blunt or penetrating) but are not on their own indicative of an orbital fracture. They may be present if the trauma is associated with globe injury in addition to diplopia associated with orbital wall fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrismus \u003C/strong\u003Eis not associated with orbital wall fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Orbital wall fracture is associated with extraocular muscle entrapment that leads to paretic and restrictive diplopia"],"references":["Heath Jeffrey R, Dobes J, Chen FK. Eye injuries. Aust J Gen Pract. 2022; 51:476-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28792"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-27T18:58:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-27T18:58:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43803"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":f